The paper deals with counting crossing-free structures on a set of points in the plane, which is a classic problem in computational geometry (cs.CG). The algorithmic techniques used involve dynamic programming and the concept of onion layers, which are common in computational geometry and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the complexity of the problem and proves hardness results, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper mentions the enumeration of matchings and cycles, which are topics in graph theory (cs.GT).
